 Through the Kileleshwa Ward Neighborhood Association (KIWANA), the residents have written to the aspirants inviting them for interviews on Saturday, April 9 at the Kileleshwa Covenant Community Church. According to the letters signed by the association’s manager Sam Mwaura, aspirants will be required to provide their CVs for an overview of their qualifications. “The purpose of the meeting will be to give the opportunity for the community to meet the aspirants and for you to introduce yourself and explain what you plan to do for Kileleleshwa,” reads the letter in part. “The introduction will be in the form of a brief overview of your CV which should include your academic qualifications We would be grateful if you could please email a copy to KIWANA or send it by WhatsApp to the KIWANA phone number.” The association will be also be assessing the aspirants integrity in line with Chapter 6 of the Constitution and how they  plan to engage in the fight against corruption. “Also your understanding of the national values and principles of governance as set out in Article 10 of Chapter 2,” adds the letter. Several aspirants are expected to attend the session with each presentation estimated to take about 10 minutes.  